						               													<description>Muzundrum is a game of creating musical triads and scales by placing 12-sided musical dice on a hexagon-based playing board.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;From the publishers' website:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Muzundrum is a crossword-style game of music theory developed by composer J S Kingfisher. Players interlace 12-sided musical dice to form scales and triads on a giant honeycomb, forming unique tonal weaves... it&amp;rsquo;s great for beginners, challenging for pros, and always mind-bending fun!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In the box&amp;#10;&amp;#10;21 Twelve-sided Musician&amp;rsquo;s Dice&amp;#10;The Honeycomb Gameboard&amp;#10;Embroidered dice pouch&amp;#10;Instruction Booklet&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Number of players, time required&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Muzundrum can be played by 1 to 4 musicians of any age (see &amp;ldquo;knowledge required&amp;rdquo; below); or by 2 to 4 teams of musicians (playing in teams allows musical novices to learn from their more experienced partners). The average game lasts 15 to 30 minutes.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Object of the game&amp;#10;&amp;#10;In Muzundrum, players intertwine triads with scales, rather like a musical crossword puzzle (albeit a three way one). Triads are built vertically; scales are built diagonally. Points are earned as players add to or complete triads and scales; double and triple scores are earned when dice are played in the &amp;ldquo;honeypot&amp;rdquo; cells (the ones marked with 2&amp;rsquo;s and 3&amp;rsquo;s). The game is over when all of the dice are played; points are then tallied, and the player or team with the most points wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Knowledge required&amp;#10;&amp;#10;A basic working knowledge of key centers, major scales, and triad construction is needed to play Muzundrum &amp;ndash; all stuff taught in first-year Music Theory classes and by most private music instructors. In addition to being a heap o&amp;rsquo; fun, Muzundrum is quite educational: it&amp;rsquo;s a great way to become fluent in all 12 keys.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
